ce:section.ce:para:
The main protein behind these effects is the protein tyrosine phosphatase 1 B (PTP1B), which is recognized as a key target for the treatment of type 2 diabetes and obesity. S. tamariscina extracts, in particular alcoholic extracts, contain different compounds that functions as PTP1B, such as the biflavone amentoflavone (IC50 = 7.3 μM) and various selaginellin derivatives, such as selariscinin A (IC50 = 4.6 μM), selaginellin U (IC50 = 13.8 μM), and selaginellin M (IC50 = 11.5 μM) (Na et al., 2007; Nguyen et al., 2015; Hung et al., 2016; Le et al., 2017) (Fig. 4
                        ). These compounds behaving as insulin-mimetic could be useful to treat type 2 diabetes and serve as a guide to design and develop more potent PTP1B inhibitors. Selariscinin A is the most potent compound in the family, but STE extracts contain a complete series of selaginellin/selariscinin derivatives. Recently two new compounds, designated selariscinin F and G (Fig. 5
                        ), have been isolated from S. tamariscina (Wen et al., 2020), as well as dimeric selaginellin derivatives designated selapiginellin A, selaginpulvilin U, and diselaginellin A (Woo et al., 2021). Their effect on glucose blood level has not been reported yet. Biflavone-type PTP1B inhibitors with antihyperglycemia activity, analogues of amentatoflavone, can be found in other Selaginella species (Xu et al., 2019b).
